                            </h2>                           
                        </div> <!-- end section-header -->

                        <div class="s-about__content-main grid-section-split__primary">
                            <p class="attention-getter">
                                Sciatica refers to pain that radiates along the path of the sciatic
                                 nerve, which branches from your lower back through your hips and
                                  buttocks and down each leg. It typically affects one side of your
                                   body and can vary from mild discomfort to excruciating pain.
                            </p>
                            
                                <p class="attention-getter">
                                    <h4 class="text">Causes of Sciatica: </h4>
                                    <ul>
                                     <li>Herniated Disc:</li><p>
                                        Discs act as cushions between the vertebrae in
                                         your spine. When one of these discs herniates or
                                          bulges, it can press against the sciatic nerve, 
                                          triggering pain.
                                     </p>
                                     
                                     <li>Spinal Stenosis: </li><p>
                                        This condition involves the narrowing of the spinal canal, putting
                                         pressure on the nerves, including the sciatic nerve.
                                     </p>  
                                     <li>Piriformis Syndrome: </li><p>
                                        The piriformis muscle, located in the buttocks, can sometimes irritate or 
                                        compress the sciatic nerve, leading to sciatica symptoms.
                                     </p>  
                                     <li>Injury or Trauma: </li><p>
                                        Accidents or injuries to the spine can cause inflammation
                                         or compression of the sciatic nerve, resulting in pain.

                                     </p> 
                                    </ul>  
                                    </p>  

                                    <p class="attention-getter">
                                        <h4 class="text">Symptoms of Sciatica: </h4>
                                        <ul>
                                         <li>Radiating Pain: </li><p>
                                            The hallmark symptom of sciatica is a sharp, shooting pain that radiates
                                             along the path of the sciatic nerve. This pain typically starts in the
                                              lower back or buttock and travels down the back of the thigh, often 
                                              extending below the knee and sometimes into the foot.
                                         </p>
                                         
                                         <li>Constant or Intermittent Pain: </li><p>
                                            Sciatica pain can vary from a constant, dull ache
                                             to sudden, severe pain that makes movement difficult.

                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Burning or Tingling Sensation:</li><p>
                                            Some individuals with sciatica may experience a 
                                            burning or tingling sensation (paresthesia) along 
                                            the affected leg or foot.

                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Numbness: </li><p>
                                            Sciatica can cause numbness or weakness in the leg or foot, making
                                             it difficult to move or bear weight on the affected side.
                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Pain Aggravated by Sitting or Standing: </li><p>
                                            Sitting or standing for prolonged periods may worsen sciatica pain, as
                                             it can increase pressure on the lower back and sciatic nerve.
                                         </p> 
                                        </ul>   
                                        </p>    

                                        <p class="attention-getter">
                                            <h4 class="text">How we can Aware from Sciatica: </h4>
                                            <ul>
                                             <li>Health Screenings: </li><p>
                                                Offer health screenings or wellness events where individuals 
                                                can learn about common musculoskeletal conditions, including 
                                                sciatica, and receive personalized advice from healthcare professionals. 
                                                Provide opportunities for participants to ask questions and seek guidance
                                                 on managing their symptoms.
                                             </p>
                                             
                                             <li>Symptom Recognition: </li><p>
                                                Educate individuals about the common symptoms of sciatica, such as radiating pain, 
                                                numbness, tingling, and muscle weakness in the lower back, buttocks, legs, or feet. 
                                                Encourage them to seek medical attention if they experience persistent or severe symptoms 
                                                that interfere with their daily activities.
    
                                             </p>  
                                             <li>Preventive Strategies: </li><p>
                                                Provide information about preventive strategies to reduce the risk of developing
                                                 sciatica or experiencing recurrent episodes. Emphasize the importance of maintaining
                                                  a healthy weight, practicing good posture, staying physically active, avoiding prolonged
                                                   sitting or standing, and using proper lifting techniques.
    
                                             </p>  
                                             <li>Public Awareness Campaigns: </li><p>
                                                Partner with local government agencies, nonprofit organizations,
                                                 or advocacy groups to launch public awareness campaigns about 
                                                 sciatica. Utilize traditional media channels (e.g., television, 
                                                 radio, newspapers) and digital platforms (e.g., social media, email
                                                  newsletters) to reach a diverse audience.

                                             </p>  
                                            </ul>   
                                            </p>   
                                            

        

                                    <p class="attention-getter">
                                        <h4 class="text">Prevent Sciatica: </h4>
                                        <ul>
                                         <li>Maintain a Healthy Weight: </li><p>
                                            Excess weight can exert pressure on the spine, increasing
                                             the risk of sciatica. Aim for a balanced diet and regular 
                                             exercise to maintain a healthy weight.
                                         </p>
                                         
                                         <li>Practice Good Posture: </li><p>
                                            Poor posture can strain the spine and contribute to sciatica. 
                                            Practice proper ergonomics when sitting, standing, and lifting
                                             heavy objects.
                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Exercise Regularly: </li><p>
                                            Engage in activities that strengthen the core muscles and support the spine,
                                             such as walking, swimming, or yoga.
                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Quit Smoking: </li><p>
                                            Smoking can contribute to disc degeneration and impair blood flow to the spine, increasing the risk of sciatica.
                                         </p> 
                                        </ul>  
                                        </p>

                                        
                                    <p class="attention-getter">
                                        <h4 class="text">Treatment for Sciatica: </h4>
                                        <ul>
                                         <li>Pain Medications:</li><p>
                                            Over-the-counter pain relievers such as ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin) or naproxen (Aleve)
                                             can help reduce inflammation and alleviate sciatica pain. In more severe cases, your
                                              doctor may prescribe muscle relaxants or stronger pain medications.
                                         </p>
                                         
                                         <li>Physical Therapy: </li><p>
                                            A tailored physical therapy program can help strengthen the muscles surrounding 
                                            the spine, improve flexibility, and alleviate pressure on the sciatic nerve. Physical
                                             therapists may use techniques such as stretching exercises, gentle massage, and low-impact
                                              aerobic conditioning to help manage sciatica symptoms.
                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Hot and Cold Therapy:</li><p>
                                            Alternating between hot and cold packs can provide temporary relief from sciatica 
                                            pain by reducing inflammation and numbing the affected area. Apply a cold pack for 
                                            15-20 minutes several times a day during the acute phase of pain, then switch to heat 
                                            therapy with a warm compress or heating pad to relax muscles and improve blood flow.
                                         </p>  
                                         <li>Epidural Steroid Injections: </li><p>
                                            In cases where conservative treatments fail to provide relief, your doctor may recommend 
                                            epidural steroid injections. These injections deliver corticosteroids directly into the 
                                            space around the spinal nerve roots, reducing inflammation and providing temporary pain relief.
                                             Multiple injections may be necessary for optimal results.
                                         </p> 
                                        </ul>  
                                        </p>
              

                            
